None the less I also know of at least one non nuclear<br>
solar system cruiser/starship that could be made theoreticly.<br>
<br>
 The non nuclear space cruiser can be created in the following way:This is to build a spacecraft that is powerd by a combination of a solar/laser sail, and a solar electric ion<br>
or plasma drive propulsion system.<br>
<br>
 At 1 au (93,000,000) miles solar sunlight flux is 1400<br>
watts per square meter of area. Solar flux declines by the inverse square of the distance. At 2 it declines 4 times, at<br>
10 au it declines 100 times and at 100 au it declines by<br>
10,000 times in strength.If I make a sqaure solar sail that measures 1000 meters by 1000 meters , the sail area is<br>
1,000,000 sqaure meters, and the solar flux collected by the sail is 1.,400,000,000 watts.<br>
<br>
 The thrust of a solar sail = 2 * (total solar flux, on the sail) /300,000,000 kilograms. 1.4 gigawatts will thus produce 9.33 kilograms of thrust which is 93.3  newtons or about 20 pounds. We can use the solar sail as a collector/mirror  to reflect this sunlight onto photovotaic arrays (solar cells) which can convert potentially 20 % of the solar flux into electric power. <br>
<br>
This could then  provide 280 megawatts of electric power to run an electric ion or plasma drive.  At 2 au the thrust would be down to 5 pounds, and then the  electric power generation potential would decline to 70 megawatts.<br>
<br>
 At 10 au which is the distance to saturn thrust would be down to .2 pound but electric power generation potential potential for an ion/plasma drive would be still 2.8 megawatts.<br>
<br>
 If we  increase the solar sail size to 10,000 meters by 10,000<br>
meters we can generate 2000 pounds of thrust at 1 au.<br>
The electric power generation potential would be 28 gigawatts. At 10 au we could get 20 pounds of thrust from the sail, and 280 ,000,000  watts of electric power this way.<br>
At 50 au thrust would be .8 pounds from the sail, but we could<br>
still generate 11 megawatts of electric power for an ion or plasma drive.<br>
<br>
 11 megewatts can make 2 grams of ion beam mass  <br>
go 100 km/sec, and generate 1320 pounds of thrust.<br>
Provided the solar powered vessel does not weigh more <br>
then 1,320,000 pounds at 50 au a 1 millimeter per second acceleration would be possible even at 50 au with the ion drive.These results can be improved by using bigger solar sails, and or lower weight vehicles<br>
<br>
<br>
